            "answer_text": "For Huawei, the major impact of the ban is only the consumer business, 5G base stations and other businesses have little impact, and the stocking of chips such as 7nm can last for several years. However, the base station business is different. China is the world\u2019s largest 5G market. The total number of base stations to be built in 2020 is expected to be 800,000. After deducting the construction last year, the base station market is not only supplied by Huawei. Base station shipments are about hundreds of thousands of units. Based on this, the ban will not have a great impact on Huawei\u2019s base station business. Huawei has previously prepared a large number of components and base stations do not require too high-end technology. Some are 7nm, and many are 28nm and the above process. On the whole, Huawei's 5G base station-related business can be supported for several years, and there is still time to solve the problem of replacement of chips and parts. Since 2019, Huawei has begun to produce 5G base stations without American components. Although from an economic point of view, if all the parts are produced by themselves, it is not very cost-effective and inefficient, and may not be able to make every part at first, but Huawei's move can let the company itself not be controlled by the others. Huawei\u2019s new suppliers are basically the Chinese domestic companies, such as base station antennas: Tongyu Communications, Sega Technology, Fei Rongda, etc.; PCB: Shennan Circuits, Shanghai Electronics Co., Ltd., etc.; small base stations: Bangxun Technology, Sunsea Intelligent, etc.; RF Front end: Zhuoshengwei, Wuhan Fangu, etc.; Optical fiber and cable: Hengtong Optoelectronics, YOFC, Zhongtian Technology; Optical module: Accelink Technology, Zhongji Innolux, etc. It can be seen that Huawei's suppliers are basically taken over by the Chinese domestic manufacturers. Thus, that so-called news of that article in Nikkei has nothing new but obsolete information of the past before Huawei started the part replacement program. The threshold for building a base station is high and the versatility is low. This places high demands on communication equipment vendors, and it is not just a matter of using other people's technology and patents. It can be seen that Huawei is fully capable of this challenge. Judging from the base station orders that Huawei has already sold (more than 50 huge orders), the international influence is still considerable. For example, according to the 2018 annual reports of some US technology giants, a considerable part of their revenue comes from China: Qualcomm 67%, Intel 26%, and Nvidia 24%. All those American high tech firms will suffer losses without the Chinese orders because they will be replaced by the Chinese domestic companies such as BOE, TCL, Goodix, Zhaoyi, SMIC, Wingtech, and San'an. In summary, Huawei will be able to continue its 5G program more effectively independent of the Americans. It is a done deal. Huawei will make China great first. ",
